## Obligations

1. The Counterparty shall perform the services described in the *Statement of Work* with reasonable skill and care.
2. The Company shall pay the agreed fees within thirty days of receipt of a valid invoice.
3. Both parties shall keep the other's confidential information confidential per the *Confidentiality* clause below.
4. Both parties shall comply with applicable law, including the *Data Protection* clause below.

## Data protection

Where the Counterparty processes personal data on behalf of the Company under this agreement, it does so as a processor under UK GDPR and the parties shall execute the Company's standard *Data Processing Agreement* before any such processing begins.

Both parties shall notify the other of any personal data breach affecting data processed under this agreement within twenty-four hours of becoming aware of it.

## Limitation of liability

Neither party excludes or limits liability for (a) death or personal injury caused by negligence, (b) fraud or fraudulent misrepresentation, or (c) any other liability that cannot lawfully be limited.

Subject to the above, each party's aggregate liability under this agreement in any twelve-month period is limited to the fees paid or payable under this agreement in that period.

## Termination

Either party may terminate this agreement for material unremedied breach, for insolvency of the other party, or on the notice period set out in the *Term* clause above.

On termination the Counterparty shall return or destroy the Company's confidential information and shall hand over any deliverables in progress. Clauses that by their nature are intended to survive termination — *Confidentiality*, *IP*, *Limitation of Liability* — do so.

## Governing law and jurisdiction

This agreement is governed by the laws of England and Wales. The parties submit to the exclusive jurisdiction of the courts of England and Wales for any dispute arising out of or in connection with this agreement.

## Data protection summary

We process personal data lawfully, fairly and transparently. The lawful bases on which we rely are recorded in the *Record of Processing Activities*. The retention periods are recorded in the *Data Retention Policy*.

Data subjects have rights — access, rectification, erasure, restriction, portability, objection — which are exercised via the *Subject Access Request Process*. We respond within one month unless an extension is justified and notified to the subject.

## Security summary

- Strong authentication (MFA) for every account that touches customer data, money, or production.
- Encryption at rest and in transit for every system that stores customer data.
- Least-privilege access; access is granted on need, reviewed quarterly, and revoked promptly when an engagement ends.
- Logging and monitoring on every production system, with alerts routed to the on-call rotation.
- An incident response process that the team has practised at least once.

The long form of each of the above is in the *Security Policy*.

## Third parties

We use third parties — software vendors, contractors, advisers — to do work we do not do ourselves. We pick them on the basis of fit, quality and price, in that order.

Every third-party relationship is logged in the *Tool Stack Register* or the *Subscription Cost Register*. The owner of the relationship is the person responsible for renewal, escalation and review. No third party is engaged without a written contract.

## Legal compliance

We comply with the laws of every country in which we operate. Where the laws of two countries conflict, we comply with the stricter and document the reason in the *Decision Log*.

We do not interpret the law informally. Where a question has legal consequence — a contract, a privacy decision, an employment matter — we take advice from a qualified professional. The cost of advice is recorded in the budget; the absence of advice is recorded as a risk.

